{
  "answer": "Across the Urdu corpus, 'rind' (libertine, from Persian) is a stock Sufi-poetic archetype: the free-spirited person who drinks wine (mai), haunts the tavern (maikada), and appears to violate religious law — but whose apparent transgression is a spiritual posture, not mere immorality. The rind is always set against the 'zahid' (ascetic/pious preacher), and that opposition is the site where the rind does its theological work.\n\nFour interlocking functions emerge across Ghalib, Zauq, and Iqbal:\n\n1. **Critique of performative/transactional piety.** Zauq's chapter titled 'Rind-e-kharaab-haal ko zaahid na chhed tu' (Do not disturb the ruined-state libertine, O ascetic — Diwan-e-Zauq, ch. 46) tells the zahid to settle his own accounts with God instead of judging the rind. The zahid is explicitly called 'zaahid-e-do-rang' (two-faced ascetic), a hypocrite. Ghalib makes the same move (ch. 43): 'O pious man, why push the cup away? / This is true wine; a fly's sick gift is not real' — the zahid's rejection of wine is itself a form of false piety. The rind's outward rule-breaking exposes the zahid's inward corruption.\n\n2. **Divine love (ishq) over legal calculation (aql).** Wine (baada/mai) in this tradition is always a metaphor for the intoxication of divine love. The rindaan do not drink out of vice but out of love. Ghalib's ch. 167 captures this: 'Jaadaad-e-baada-noshi-e-rindaan hai shash-jihat / Ghaafil gumaan kare hai ke geeti kharaab hai' — translated as 'The mystic owns the world in every way; / The fool believes the cosmos in decay is.' The rindaan's wine-drinking is not ruin but possession of all six directions, i.e., total spiritual ownership of existence. The heedless (ghaafil) who see them as corrupt have mistaken appearance for reality.\n\n3. **Non-dual transcendence of outward states.** Iqbal, Bang-e-Dara Part 1, ch. 6, declares: 'He is no mystic in my eyes, O Sāqi bright, / Who separates ecstatic joy from sober light' (transliterating: 'Meri nigaah mein woh rind hi nahin saaqi / Jo hoshiyaari o masti mein imtiyaaz kare'). The true rind does not oscillate between sobriety and intoxication — he has dissolved that distinction. This is a statement of non-dual consciousness, where outward states (drunk/sober, sinful/pious) cease to be spiritually determinative.\n\n4. **Malamati self-erasure and the Hallaj connection.** In Iqbal's 'Zuhd aur Rindi' (BD1, ch. 44), a zahid reports that Iqbal 'knows the Sinner's path, the Law's decree / In mystic lore, a new Mansur is he.' Mansur is al-Hallaj, martyred for declaring 'Ana'l-Haqq' (I am the Truth). Comparing the rind to Hallaj locates the figure in the malamati (blame-taking) tradition: the rind courts social censure precisely in order to annihilate the ego (nafs) and dissolve into God. Outward ruin is the cost of inward union.\n\n5. **Tajalli (divine self-disclosure) in beauty.** Ghalib identifies himself as 'rind-e-shaahid-baaz' (ch. 144) — translated as 'that rogue mystic, that connoisseur of beauty.' 'Shaahid' means both 'beautiful one' and 'witness/manifestation.' Gazing at shaahidaan is a Sufi practice of seeing divine tajalli (self-disclosure) in created beauty — grounded in wahdat al-wujud (unity of being). The rind who pursues beauty is pursuing God's own manifestation in the world.\n\nIn sum: the rind is the corpus's primary instrument for critiquing exoteric, legalistic Islam from within the Sufi tradition. It does not reject religion but internalizes it — replacing fear-driven, heaven-calculating observance with love-drunk, ego-annihilating union. The zahid is always implicitly the foil: he keeps the law but misses God; the rind breaks the law and finds God.",
